## Event System / Kafka

### Architecture
- Apache Kafka (via Strimzi) handles all async messaging
- Topic naming convention: `{{ .Project.Metadata.Name }}.<domain>.<event-name>`
- All events use JSON with a standard envelope

### Event Envelope
```typescript
interface EventEnvelope<T> {
  id: string;           // UUID v4
  type: string;         // e.g., "user.created"
  source: string;       // Service name
  timestamp: string;    // ISO 8601
  correlationId: string;
  data: T;
}
```

### Publishing Events
{{ if .Computed.HasDapr }}- Use Dapr pub/sub binding (preferred):
```typescript
await daprClient.pubsub.publish('pubsub', 'topic-name', eventData);
```{{ else }}- Use the shared Kafka producer from `{{ .Computed.PrimaryScope }}/kafka-client`:
```typescript
import { createProducer } from '{{ .Computed.PrimaryScope }}/kafka-client';

const producer = createProducer({ brokers: config.KAFKA_BROKERS });
await producer.send('{{ .Project.Metadata.Name }}.domain.event-name', envelope);
```{{ end }}

### Consuming Events
{{ if .Computed.HasDapr }}- Subscribe via Dapr subscription component in Helm values
- Handler receives deserialized data at the configured route{{ else }}- Use the shared Kafka consumer:
```typescript
import { createConsumer } from '{{ .Computed.PrimaryScope }}/kafka-client';

const consumer = createConsumer({
  brokers: config.KAFKA_BROKERS,
  groupId: 'my-service',
});

consumer.subscribe('{{ .Project.Metadata.Name }}.domain.event-name', async (event) => {
  // Process event
});
```{{ end }}

### Critical Rules
1. Events must be **idempotent** — consumers may receive duplicates
2. Always include `correlationId` for distributed tracing
3. Never put sensitive data (passwords, tokens) in event payloads
4. Consumer group ID must match the service name
5. New topics require a Strimzi KafkaTopic CR in the Kafka Helm chart
6. Failed events go to `<topic>.dlq` (dead letter queue) — monitor these
